/gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Harley</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Powell</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF036019%2F1"><gtr:id>6C64CAA8-2417-4E62-AC3F-835F146FF13C</gtr:id><gtr:title>An Evolutionary Theory of Knowledge Management in Practice: A Study of Management Consulting</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F036019/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The research project seeks to explore knowledge management practices, both explicit and emergent, in the context of management consulting organisations. The aim of this research is to better understand which practices work within these knowledge intensive organisations.
&lt;br />Despite evolutionary theory being one of the dominant paradigms in contemporary management research, previous research on knowledge management has adopted a surprisingly static perspective. Current research does not situate an organisation's current approach to knowledge management within the context of the historical approaches employed. Instead current research has tended to conduct cross-sectional analysis with the view of identifying characteristics that drive the current knowledge management approaches within the organisations studied. Current practices in knowledge management are then argued to be successful, while previous approaches are argued to be unsuccessful. This research is novel in that it addresses this shortcoming by situating the organisation's current knowledge management practices within the context of its historical approach to knowledge management.
&lt;br />The research aims to understand whether organisations maintain a consistent approach to knowledge management, as is argued for in the literature, or change this approach over time. If organisations do change their approach to knowledge management over time, it raises the question as to why this approach changes and whether organisations follow common or divergent paths in their evolving approach to knowledge management.
